#Installing Theamus

So, you want to install Theamus, do you? Well here's a run down on how you do it.

1. [Set up your server](#setup-server)
1. [Download Theamus](#download-theamus)
1. [Install Theamus](#install-theamus)

---

###<a href="#" name="setup-server">Set up your server</a>

In order for Theamus to work properly, there's a few things that need to be done on your server.

- [Enable .htaccess](#enable-htaccess)
- [Enable PHP modules](#enable-php-modules)

####<a href="#" name="enable-htaccess">Enabling .htaccess</a>

Enable the rewrite module via apache:

```
sudo a2enmod rewrite
```

Sometime there's an extra step. You need to enable `AllowOverride` in the apache configuration file (or based on your site configuration file in `sites-available`).

__On Ubuntu:__
```
sudo vim /etc/apache2/apache2.conf

```

Search for `AllowOverride` by using `/AllowOverride`

```
<Directory /var/www>
    Options  Indexes FollowSymLinks
    AllowOverride None -> (change "None" to "All")
    Require all granted
</Directory>
```

Restart Apache

```
sudo service apache2 restart
```

####<a href="#" name="enable-php-modules">Enabling PHP Modules</a>

There's a few PHP modules that need to be enabled for Theamus to work properly. Those modules are:
- cURL
- MySQL driver for PDO
- mcrypt

__Enabling cURL:__

Theamus uses cURL to download the latest versions of itself for the one click update feature. Also, you can use Theamus to make AJAX like calls with the help of cURL.
```
sudo apt-get install php5-curl
```

__Checking PDO:__

This should be on by default, but to test, run:
```
php -m | grep "PDO"
```

__Enabling mcrypt:__
```
sudo php5enmod mcrypt
```

Restart Apache
```
sudo service apache2 restart
```

##<a href="#" name="download-theamus">Download Theamus</a>

1. Download the latest version of Theamus from it's [GitHub Releases page.](https://github.com/helllomatt/Theamus/releases)
1. Extract the files to a location of your choosing
1. Change file ownership and file permissions!

```
sudo chown -R www-data /var/www/theamus
find /var/www/theamus -type d -exec chmod 755 {} \; && find /var/www/theamus -type f -exec chmod 644 {} \;
```

&nbsp;

##<a href="#" name="install-theamus">Install Theamus</a>

After you've placed the files and changed their permissions/ownership, there's one more thing you need to do before you can browse to the installer on the web. That thing? __Create a database__. You're going to need an empty database, and a user with access to it before the installer will even take.


Navigate to your Theamus installation in your browser `http://localhost/theamus` and you'll be greeted with the installer. Theamus automatically detects if it has been installed, so there's no need to go to some fancy installation path.

<img width="100%" alt="Installation Home Image" src="data:image/png;base64,"/>

Once you've gotten started on the installation, you'll be sent to a dependency check page. You've set everything up on your server, but Theamus needs to check it as well. If something doesn't pass, you'll see a red "X" - a green check mark if it does pass.

__Note:__ _Theamus doesn't check for the mcrypt extension. Make sure that's turned on!_


<img width="100%" alt="Dependencies Check Image" src="data:image/png;base64,"/>

Everything's good? Now for the fun stuff: form filling!

<img width="100%" alt="Installation Form Image" src="data:image/png;base64,"/>

####Site Name
This is the name of your website. It will show up in the title bar of your browser, or in any email that your website will send out, for example.


####Database Configuration

|Field|Description|
|---|---|
|Database Host|The server address of your MySQL installation|
|Database Username|The login username of a user with full rights to the newly created, and empty, database|
|Database Password|The password of the user above|
|Database Name|The name of the database that will hold the tables created by Theamus. _The user must have full rights to this database!_|

####First User
This is the first user created for your website. It will have full administrator privileges!

|Field|Description|
|---|---|
|Username|The login username of the "administrator" user. _Must be at least 4 characters long and cannot be changed by Theamus after the installation._|
|Password|The login password related to the above username. _Must be at least 4 characters long._|
|Email Address|A valid email address associated to the administrator account.|
|First Name|Your first name|
|Last Name|Your surname|

###Advanced Options
Up until now, all of the fields are required. The advanced options are just extra. If you want to customize more, you can.

####Database Customization

__Table Prefix:__ A prefix associated to each Theamus related table.

The reason for prefixes is to allow features to name their tables whatever they want without having to worry about conflicting with another feature's tables. When a feature is installed, the table prefix is randomized, but you don't need to know that. You only need to know the name of the table. Let Theamus deal with the rest.

Another reason is for managing tables when upgrading or installing. Having randomized table prefixes allows them to act as unique ID's. This opens up the ability to update a table when upgrading a feature, or deleting them when deleting the feature. Theamus doesn't have to worry about deleting the wrong one with the prefix system.

####Email Configuration

Emails are sent out through __SMTP__.

|Field|Description|
|---|---|
|Host|The host address of the email server|
|Protocol|The protocol the email server uses|
|Port|The port the server listens to|
|Login Username|The user/email address that Theamus will be sending the emails through|
|Login Password|The password to the username above|

####Security

Both of these fields are critical. If you lose either of these salts, all of your users will be locked out permanently. __Be sure to make note of these!__

These fields get written to a file, not the database. Check out `ROOT/config.php` to see what they are. Back that file up too!

Both of these fields must be at least 5 characters long. If you leave either one blank, a random string 32 characters long will be generated.

|Field|Description|
|---|---|
|Password Salt|This is a string of characters that will be appended to every password. The longer the better!|
|Session Salt|This is a string of characters that will be appended to every session cookie.|

###Developer Options

__Turn on Developer Mode:__ Gives you a few more options in the admin panel, like a quick way to create features, for example. Also loads the full sized Javascript and CSS files instead of the minified versions, adding to the load time of your page. It turns on error reporting too, which will show any errors on the page. (E_ALL)

__Note:__ You _cannot_ turn off Developer Mode from any Theamus window. If you want to disable it, you need to look in the `settings` table for a `developer_mode` column and change the value to 0. You _can_ turn off error reporting and leave developer mode on through the admin panels, though. Go to `Settings -> Settings (tab) -> Display Errors?` and uncheck it to turn off error reporting.
